# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] The **1988 McDonald's Bicentennial Youth Cricket World Cup** was an international cricket tournament played in Australia from 28 February to 13 March 1988.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] Sponsored by McDonald's, it was the inaugural edition of what is now the Under-19 Cricket World Cup, and formed part of the celebrations for the Australian Bicentenary.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was primarily organised by the Australian Cricket Board (ACB), with only limited oversight from the International Cricket Conference (ICC).
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams participated, with the seven Test-playing ICC members joined by a composite team of players from ICC associate members.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] Australia defeated Pakistan in the final by five wickets, with England and the West Indies being the losing semi-finalists.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] The tournament play-offs were held at Adelaide Oval, with the other matches held at country venues in the states of New South Wales, South Australia, and Victoria.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] Australia's Brett Williams was the leading run-scorer at the tournament, while his teammate Wayne Holdsworth and Pakistan's Mushtaq Ahmed were the joint leading wicket-takers.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1988-youth-cricket-world-cup] Players at the tournament had to be 18 years or younger on 1 January 1987, restricting participation to those born before 1 January 1968.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **1998 MTN ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was an international limited-overs cricket tournament played in South Africa from 11 January to 1 February 1998.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Sponsored by the MTN Group, it was the second edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup, coming ten years after the inaugural tournament in 1988, and the first to be held in South Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Sixteen teams participated at the 1998 World Cup, up from only eight at the previous edition.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] After an initial group stage, the top eight teams played off in a super league to decide the tournament champions, with the non-qualifiers playing a separate "plate" competition.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was won by England, which defeated New Zealand in the final to win its first and only title.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand have failed to reach the final since then, whilst England have qualified for the final in 2022 but lost to India.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Matches were held at venues around the country, though primarily in the interior, with the main final held at Wanderers Stadium in Johannesburg.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] West Indian batsman Chris Gayle led the tournament in runs, while his teammate Ramnaresh Sarwan and Zimbabwe's Mluleki Nkala were the joint leading wicket-takers.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The twelve ICC members that had qualified their senior teams for the 1999 World Cup also automatically qualified their under-19 teams for the 1998 Under-19 World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Of those teams, nine were Test-playing countries and three were ICC associate members.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The other four teams were invited to the tournament based on criteria set by the ICC – unlike at later editions, only one regional qualification tournament, the 1997 Youth Asia Cup, was played.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool A was known as the Bradman Pool, after former Australian batsman Sir Donald Bradman.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool B was known as the Cowdrey Pool, after former English batsman Sir Colin Cowdrey.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool C was known as the Gavaskar Pool, after former Indian batsman Sunil Gavaskar.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool D was known as the Sobers Pool, after former West Indian all-rounder Sir Garfield Sobers.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The plate competition was contested by the eight teams that failed to qualify for the Super League.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool A was known as the Magiet Pool, after South African administrator Rushdie Magiet.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool B was known as the Procter Pool, after former South African all-rounder Mike Procter.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool A was known as the D'Olivera Pool, after former England international Basil D'Oliveira.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/1998-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pool B was known as the Pollock Pool, after former South African batsman Graeme Pollock.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **2000 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was an international limited-overs cricket tournament played in Sri Lanka from 11 to 28 January 2000.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] It was the third edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup and the first to be held in Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The 2000 World Cup was contested by sixteen teams, including three making their tournament debuts.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Portions of the group stage were heavily impacted by rain, especially in Group C, where only two matches could be played to completion.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] In the final, played at Colombo's Sinhalese Sports Club, India defeated Sri Lanka by six wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Both teams had made the final for the first time.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Indian all-rounder Yuvraj Singh was named player of the tournament, while South Africa's Graeme Smith was the leading run-scorer and Pakistan's Zahid Saeed was the leading wicket-taker.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The nine full members of the International Cricket Council (ICC) qualified automatically for the World Cup, while another seven teams qualified via other paths.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Bangladesh and Nepal qualified as the top two teams at the 1999 Youth Asia Cup, while Ireland and the Netherlands did likewise through the 1999 European Under-19 Championship.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The ICC Africa Under-19 Championships were not established until 2001, but Kenya and Namibia were invited to the World Cup as the top ICC associate members in Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2000-under-19-cricket-world-cup] There was also no qualification tournament held in the Americas development region, with instead a combined regional team being fielded (for the first and only time).
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2002-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **2002 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was played in New Zealand from 19 January to 9 February 2002.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2002-under-19-cricket-world-cup] A total of 16 sides competed in the tournament with Australia defeating South Africa in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2002-under-19-cricket-world-cup] It was the fourth edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup and the first to be held in New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2002-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Zimbabwe's Tatenda Taibu was named Man of the Tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **2004 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was an international limited-overs cricket tournament played in Bangladesh from 15 February to 5 March 2004.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] It was the fifth edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup and the first to be held in Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The 2004 World Cup was contested by sixteen teams, including one (Uganda) making its tournament debut.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan and the West Indies eventually progressed to the final, played at the Bangabandhu National Stadium in Dhaka, where Pakistan won by 25 runs to claim their maiden title.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] This was the first appearance of the West Indies in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2004-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Indian batsman Shikhar Dhawan was named player of the tournament as the leading run-scorer, while Bangladesh's Enamul Haque was the leading wicket-taker.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **2006 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was played in Sri Lanka from 2 to 15 February 2006.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] It was the sixth edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The final was played between the defending champion Pakistan and India in Colombo, which Pakistan won by 38 runs, enabling them to become the first back-to-back champions of the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] A dramatic final was played between Pakistan and India in Colombo.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] After Pakistan set a very low target of 110 runs to win for India, a stunning Pakistani bowling performance devastated India's top-order batsmen, taking the first six wickets for nine runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2006-under-19-cricket-world-cup] India was eventually dismissed for 71 within 19 overs, enabling Pakistan to become the first country ever to defend the title successfully and become back-to-back champions of the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The **2008 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup** was held in Malaysia from 17 February 2008 to 2 March 2008.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] It was the seventh edition of the Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The opening ceremony took place on 15 February 2008.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The final was played between South Africa and India, with the latter winning the rain-affected match by 12 runs on the Duckworth–Lewis method.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The matches took place at three locations: Kuala Lumpur, Johor and Penang.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The league stage of the tournament consisted of four groups of four teams each.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] Each team would play once with every team in the group.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The groups would be stationed at their respective venues for the group stage.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/2008-under-19-cricket-world-cup] The figures in brackets indicate respective seedings.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The **Afghanistan national under-19 cricket team** (Pashto: **د افغانستان ۱۹ کلنو لوبډله**) represents Afghanistan in under-19 international cricket.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan has qualified for the Under-19 Cricket World Cup on seven occasions.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The team's first tournament was the 2010 World Cup in New Zealand, which they reached by finishing runner-up to Ireland in the 2009 World Cup Qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan has qualified for every subsequent World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Although the team placed 16th and last in its first tournament in 2010, it rapidly became one of the leading under-19 teams in Asia.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan finished seventh at the 2014 World Cup in the UAE, setting a new record for the best finish by an ICC associate member (equalled by Namibia in 2016).
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] After becoming an ICC full member, Afghanistan reached the semi-finals of the 2018 Under-19 World Cup in New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Outside of the Under-19 World Cup, Afghanistan participates in the annual ACC Under-19 Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The team won the tournament in 2017, defeating Pakistan in the final.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan also plays occasional bilateral series against other Asian under-19 teams.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The team reached the semi-finals in the 2022 Under-19 World Cup, where they lost to England.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The team played in the 2010 Under-19 Cricket World Cup in New Zealand.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan were drawn in Group A, where they played England, Hong Kong and India.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan got a wooden spoon in this World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan played in the 2012 Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] They played against Pakistan, New Zealand and Scotland.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan had qualified for 2014 Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] They were drawn against Australia, Bangladesh & Namibia in group B who they beat, qualifying for Super league, where they lost to South Africa.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] They finished tournament well by securing 7th position.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] The team made it to the semifinals of the 2016 ACC Under-19 Asia Cup, losing out to India by 77 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] In the league stages of the tournament Afghanistan lost their first match, being defeated by Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] However, they won their next two matches against Pakistan and Singapore.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] They advanced to the semifinals on the basis of NRR.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] Afghanistan won the 2017 ACC Under-19 Asia Cup, defeating Pakistan in the final by a huge margin of 185 runs.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] In the league stages, Afghanistan won their matches against Pakistan and UAE but lost to Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] They faced Nepal in the semifinals, whom they defeated by 7 wickets.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] In the 2025 ACC Under-19 Asia Cup, Afghanistan failed to proceed beyond the group stage, where they were beaten by both Bangladesh and Sri Lanka and managed only a single win, in an "inconsequential" last group game against Nepal.
[src:afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team/afghanistan-national-under-19-cricket-team] All records listed are for under-19 One Day International (ODI) matches only.
